      "text": "Now I have a very comprehensive picture. Let me also look at the WER reports more closely and check for the actual BSOD crash dumps, and check for the NVIDIA driver which is quite old (2023).\n\nKey findings so far:\n1. **System**: HP OMEN Laptop 15-ce0xx with i5-7300HQ (Kaby Lake), 16GB mixed RAM, GTX 1050\n2. **No minidump files** - either minidump is disabled or the BSOD didn't write one\n3. **No explicit WHEA error events** in the logs we could parse (Italian locale causing issues)\n4. **Mixed RAM**: SK Hynix + Samsung at 2400MHz\n5. **NVIDIA driver**: 31.0.15.3179 dated April 2023 - VERY OLD\n6. **Intel HD 630 driver**: 31.0.101.2140 dated Nov 2025 - more recent\n7. **BIOS**: F.24 - need to check if this is current\n8. **Virtual memory warning**: chrome.exe using 3.5GB, vmmem using 1.1GB, opencode using 860MB\n9. **TPM errors**: Secure boot variable update failed\n10. **XTU3SERVICE timeout**: Intel Extreme Tuning service failing to start\n11. **Disk health**: All healthy (ADATA SSD, HGST HDD, Msft Virtual Disk)\n12. **Desktop Window Manager crash** at 02:38 with exit code 0xc00001ad\n\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR is a critical hardware error. On this HP OMEN with i5-7300HQ (Kaby Lake), the most common causes are:\n1. CPU VRM/power delivery issues (common in laptops)\n2. Thermal throttling leading to hardware errors\n3. RAM incompatibility (mixed brands!)\n4. BIOS/firmware issues\n5. NVIDIA GPU power management issues\n\nThe XTU3SERVICE timeout is VERY suspicious - it suggests Intel's power management/tuning is having issues.\n\nLet me compile the full analysis now.",
